THIS little volume, prepared as an experiment, needs no preface. The Editors have had before them the editions of Oudendorp WVeber and &Veiscz with several others for occasional reference. But the notes are in the main their own, and have been written by them in concert, Mr Haskins supplying the bulk of the matter, and prefixing thereto a chronological table and an abstract of the contents of the book. Mr Heitland has supplied the life of Lucan and remarks

on the Pharsalia which form the Introduction, and

has also made an Index -to the noteS. It may be

added that brevity has been studied throughout.

CAMBRmoE, May 1875.
